But if it works for ye , go on =) <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Master Azzitay Flammenpfad, Ratsmitglied <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.der-schatten.com" target="top">Der Schatten</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->,</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">Sage Chimaeron Emrys, Member of Wind of Tranquility</div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=winipo>Winipo</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/03 8:36 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Read Bicrius' guide...</span><hr size=1> I've always quadded in first person both as a druid and a wizard.  This was much easier as a druid since ensnare lasted  so long and I usually pulled with it, I didn't have to worry as much about outrunning them.  Recently, however, quadding as a wizard has forced me to learn how to do it in (mostly) 3rd person, since the mobs are running at full speed until I gather them up and snare them all at once.  I am only using jboots so all the spinning around to check their positions can deteriorate my lead, but 3rd person lets me look at their position while maintaining full speed ahead.  I usually go back to first person after I have them all snared, though. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=386446"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.burnix.org/images/winipo_sig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zertez>zertez</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 158<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/03 8:37 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Read Bicrius' guide...</span><hr size=1>  If you really want to solo or are worried about the best exp, quadding is probably the way to go. At first you may die a few times but once you get the hang of it, it is easy and at times can be boring.<br>
<br>
 It sounds like you have a pretty close guild, dont worry about not being in a guild that only raids if you are having fun. You seem like you are happy with your guild so enjoy the things you can do, while some raids are fun, others are horrid with the time involved, arguing over spawns, etc. <br>
<br>
 Wizards can bring a lot to a group at your level regardless some may tell you. Sure when you are with heavily twinked melee you can slow them down a little but in most cases you can hold your own. I would recommend grouping and for the times you can not find a group or you feel anti-social to quad. In my opinion with friends and guildmates, EQ is a lot more fun than staying off to yourself quadding. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nuuk01>Nuuk01</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 86<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/03 8:55 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Read Bicrius' guide...</span><hr size=1> <br>
I couldn't imagine not quadding for xp. It's something I actually enjoy too. Call me crazy but it's just very satisfying to me on that last shot when all 4 mobs go down at once.<br>
<br>
Also, quadding means you'll never have to waste time LFG. As a fairly casual player myself, this was invaluable to me. Back In my younger days, I was also very poor. I could support my need for sow potions and KEI by quadding also. The ulthork tusk quest is halfway decent. Once you reach about level 42 or 43 (depending on gear) get thee to BB and quad those dorfs. There's some good posts about it here (my own tales as well). You'll make the best xp you've ever made and about 20p to 25p per quad (in cash and prizes).<br>
<br>
Like everyone else said, you need the Staff of Temperal flux although I never quad in 3rd person view personally.<br>
<br>
Honestly, I think when you see your xp bar move 2 blues per quad, you'll be as hooked as we are.<br>
<br>
Nuuk Sfortenk<br>
61 Wizard of Mass Destruction<br>
Champions in Arms<br>
Quellious <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=garrathmoore>Garrath Moore</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br>  Posts: 655<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/2/03 9:02 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> re: quadding</span><hr size=1> Only real advice i think needs to be emphasized is LEARN TO QUAD WHERE YOU WONT DIE IF YOU SCREW UP.<br>
<br>
The poster who said try it at orc 1 has a good idea. The Karana's or any newbie zone is also a good spot to start.  Practice tagging them with the staff, rounding them up and then snaring them.  Don't worry about exp until you can do it every time.<br>
<br>
Once you learn the timing and everything you will be set.  It is exactly the same at level 34 vs. the Ulthorks in EW as it is at level 44 vs. the Spirocs in TD as it is at level 64 vs. the Golems in Plane of Valor.<br>
<br>
Learn where you won't get disheartened if you die.<br>
<br>
And get your Flux staff.  Its invaluable as a quadding tool.<br>
<br>
Master Garrath Moore<br>
Sorceror of the 64th KAAAAABOOOOOOMMM!!!<br>
